questionTemplates.text:
W: How was your vacation last month?
M: It was nice but expensive. We thought the hotel would cost 15 dollars, but it was three times that much.
{a}

W: I'm moving to a new place tomorrow. Could you possibly give me a hand?
M: Sure. Why not ask around the department and see if some of the other students will be free, too?
{a}

M: The radio costs $40, but I only have $30.
W: I have $16. Would you like to borrow it?
{a}

M: Has George returned from Europe yet?
W: Yes, but he had been only here for three days before his company sent him to Canada.
{a}

M: Christmas is around the corner. And I'm looking for a gift for my girlfriend. Any suggestions?
W: Well you have to tell me something about your girlfriend first. Also, what's your budget?
{a}

W: George. Where were you yesterday evening? I expected to see you at the concert.
M: Oh, I waited for you at the corner of your street. Then I looked for you at your flat, but the housekeeper said you were out.
{a}

W: It's always been hard to get this car into first gear. And now the clutch seems to be slipping.
M: If you leave the car with me, I will fix it for you this afternoon.
{a}

M: I'd like to have a talk with your director sometime this week. Could you arrange it for me?
W: He's rather busy these days. But I'll see what I can do.
{a}

M: Hello, this is doctor Marita from the emergency department. I have a 70-year-old patient with a fractured ankle.
W: OK, send him toward 3.
{a}

W: We do need another bookshelf in this room. But the problem is the space forit.
M: How about moving the old dining table to the kitchen?
{a}

W: You had a job interview yesterday, didn't you? How did it go?
M: Not too bad, I guess. There were about 20 candidates competing for the sales manager's job. And finally it was down to three of us, but the other two seemed better qualified.
{a}

M: Would you like to try the banana pie? It's incredible.
W: Well, to tell the truth I don't car emuch dessert.
{a}

F: What would you like to order, Sir?
M: Yes, please. I'll like a glass of beer.
{a}

W: Dr. Block, I need to take a few days off because my father is coming over to visit. And I need to show him around the city.
M: Ok, Jane. But be sure tocome back to work next week.
{a}

W: My husband often repairs watches for people.
M: Really? I have a broken one.
{a}

M: It's almost 2 in the morning. The man in next is still making such noise.
F: Annoying! Shall we call the Police?
{a}

W: Harry, the Christmas is coming soon. Let's go shopping for some presents.
M: Oh, God. Leave me alone.
{a}

M: It is nearly seven o'clock. Let's go.
F: No hurry. The party starts at seven thirty.
{a}

M: It's seven o'clock already. Mary should be home by now.
W: Oh. I forgot to tell you that she called this afternoon and told me that she was going to a party at her classmate's house and wouldn't be home until 10.
{a}

W: How did you do on the math exam, John?
M: I barely made it. It was just a passing score but better than I had expected.
{a}

W: I'd like to buy a copy of Professor Frankling's book on sea shells.
M: I'm sorry. Ms. That book has been out of print for some time now.
{a}

M: Mrs. Jones, you look very beautiful in the blue skirt, why not make one?
W: Urn... just take a measure for me.
{a}

W: Jack,I can't find Volumn Ten. Could you check for me who borrowed it?
M: Here it is, on the upper shelf, next to Volumn Two.
{a}

M: How often do you come back home?
F: Um... usually... twice a year.
{a}

M: Hello, my name is Carlson. I believe you have a room booked for me.
W: Carlson? Oh, yes, Mr. Carlson. It's a single room with a bath, on the second floor. I hope it will suit you, sir.
{a}

M: Excuse me, where do you live?
W: I live at No. 145, Shanghai Road.
{a}
